    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. I think my students might get confused if I don't explain why this is so controversial. Some people argue that substantive due process is actually a bit of a legal stretch and that judges shouldn't be 'making up' rights that aren't written in the text. How should I address those criticisms in the lesson so they understand why some legal scholars think this approach is problematic?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is indeed a contentious issue, and critics argue that it allows judges to 'create' rights that aren't explicitly stated in the Constitution, which they believe undermines the principle of judicial restraint and the original intent of the framers. This approach can lead to unpredictable and subjective interpretations of the Constitution, potentially expanding government power at the expense of individual liberties. Critics also contend that it shifts the balance of power from the legislative branch, which is directly accountable to the people, to the judiciary, which is not. By allowing judges to interpret the Constitution in ways that grant or restrict rights, substantive due process can result in rulings that reflect the personal beliefs of justices rather than the will of the electorate. This, they argue, can lead to a form of judicial activism that may not always align with the democratic process. It's essential to recognize that while substantive due process has been a powerful tool for protecting individual rights, it also raises important questions about the proper role of the judiciary and the interpretation of the Constitution.",
      "source": "target",
